body:
Not in this guild they don't. When I post in larger guilds they get more compared to this guild. But just in here, my posts usually don't go above 30 whereas most of the others' fall in the 50-60 range. The only reason I got more today was because I made a post an hour after the other person and pushed theirs down a spot. It still probably won't get as high as their posts normally. And I only posted that because that person told me exactly when to post it, whereas everyone else just figured it out on this own. I created this guild and spent years on /r/EverythingFoxes before that, I should be the most familiar with it and the biggest contributor.

I also have a lot more trouble finding the content in the first place, and making creative titles for them. For example "fluffy roll" vs what I could probably come up with "floof" or "very fluffy fox".

And everything I try to do is like this. It just shows that I fail miserably even at the smallest stuff like this.

body:
You're being too rough on yourself.

You do learn, your fox posts are good, nice titles, cute foxes- like double blep and nom. I don't really get what there is to learn about posting foxes? :p

Programming is another thing, there are beginners who know more than experienced programmers, this is because code is another sort of language, just like French or Mandarin. People have different experiences with learning a language; I for one can't learn a language even if my life depended on it. 

What's going on with you is that you don't accept or see when and where you've improved, and I know that it can be difficult to do so, after all; you're your own worst critic. However you need to understand that you have to be gentle with yourself because we both know that you're trying (and succeeding, however little you want to acknowledge that), and at the end of the day, that is all that matters. Plus, if this beginner programmer looks to be lightyears ahead of you, then I think you should take that as motivation and surpass him. 

I look up to you for being able to ask for help, that's something I could never do.
